House Resolution 275
By: Representatives Glaize of the 67th, McQueen of the 61st, and Dawson of the 65th
A RESOLUTION
1 Supporting an increase in the minimum school drop out age from 16 to 17 years old in the
2 State of Georgia; and for other purposes.
3 WHEREAS, in 2014, the State of Georgia had a high school graduation rate of 72.5 percent,
4 significantly lower than the national average of 81 percent in 2013, and states with higher
5 graduation rates have historically maintained a higher compulsory education age; and
6 WHEREAS, a previous Atlanta Regional Commission study projected that by 2020, 60
7 percent of jobs in Georgia would require post-secondary education, yet only 38 percent of
8 high school sophomores at the time were expected to pursue a degree or certificate; and
9 WHEREAS, the economic impact of high school dropouts is substantial, with dropouts from
10 the Class of 2010 alone estimated to cost the nation over $337 billion in lost wages over their
11 lifetimes; and
12 WHEREAS, the Alliance for Excellent Education found that over the course of their
13 lifetimes, high school dropouts earn about $260,000 less on average than graduates, with
14 additional research in 2006 revealing that 74 percent of dropouts later regret their decision
15 as adults; and
