16 WHEREAS, data published by the Journal of Public Economics indicates that individuals
17 with additional years of schooling report better health, lower rates of depression, and greater
18 life satisfaction; and
19 WHEREAS, a report from the National Education Association showed that nearly 71 percent
20 of incarcerated individuals lacked a high school diploma and that an additional year of
21 schooling reduces arrests by 11 to 18 percent; and
22 WHEREAS, a 2021 analysis from CNN Money found that Georgia spends approximately
23 $20,000 per year per inmate but only about $10,000 per student; and
24 WHEREAS, research consistently demonstrates that states with a higher school-leaving age
25 have better educational outcomes, higher employment rates, and greater economic stability,
26 with a 2012 article from The New York Times estimating that for every dollar invested in
27 increasing graduation rates, there is a return of $1.45 to $3.55; and
28 WHEREAS, increasing the minimum dropout age to 17 will better prepare Georgia's
29 workforce, strengthen the state's economy, and provide students with the opportunities
30 necessary for long-term success.
31 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES that
32 the members of this body support the increase of the minimum school dropout age in the
33 State of Georgia from 16 to 17 years old.
34 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the Clerk of the House of Representatives is authorized
35 and directed to make appropriate copies of this resolution available for distribution to the
36 public and the press.
